a palestinian sought by the united states 
for the 1982 bombing of a pan am jetliner was convicted tuesday of 
keeping makeshift knives in his jail cell and sentenced to eight 
months in prison 
mohammed rashid 39 has been jailed in piraeus since his arrest 
last may the us request for his extradition is still awaiting a 
decision by the supreme court 
a japanese teenager was killed and 15 people were injured when 
a bomb exploded aboard a pan am jumbo jet over hawaii the plane 
manged to land despite the hole in the fuselage 
in its verdict tuesday the threemember court of appeals gave 
rashid the option of paying a 620 fine instead of serving the 
eightmonth sentence 
greeces supreme court has twice delayed a decision on the us 
extradition petition 
the sentence for illegal possession of weapons could further 
delay any action on the extradition issue if rashid chooses not to 
pay the fine he would have to serve the jail sentence before he 
could be sent to the united states 
rashids lawyer spyros fitrakis told the court his client 
will remain jailed regardless of this decision as he is still 
waiting for the supreme court decision 
rashid claims his real name is mohammed hamdan and that he is an 
officer in the military branch of the palestine liberation 
organization the plo has provided him with a translator and has 
supported him since his arrest at the athens airport 
he told reporters during the trial i am innocent and am not a 
terrorist it is the us congress that thinks i am and is putting 
pressure on greece to send me there 
the illegal weapons charge was filed against rashid after knives 
were found by prison guards during a search of cells on feb 17 
rashid was acquitted at an earlier trial but piraeus district 
attorney antonis roussos took the case to the appeals court 
we find him guilty of illegal weapons possession but grant him 
a few mitigating circumstances said judge antonis papatheodorou 
before announcing the sentence 
the judge said the court found that rashid held onto the 
weapons because he honestly felt he feared for his life he felt he 
was under threat 
