<TEXT>
the denver city council voted monday to loosen its 
livinginsin zoning law so that unrelated people could legally 
live together in familyzoned areas 
the council voted 85 to initially approval to plans to change 
two types of zoning r0 which bans boarders or unrelated people 
from living in the same house and r1 which allows a boarder with 
a city permit 
the changes would allow two unrelated people plus close 
relatives with some exceptions to live together in areas zoned 
r0 and would permit one boarder related or unrelated without a 
city permit 
about 60 percent of the city 505000 people live under r1 
zoning and 7 percent fall under r0 
the changes in the socalled livinginsin law come up for 
second and final action april 24 
the amended laws would still forbid nieces nephews aunts 
uncles and inlaws from living together said city councilwoman 
cathy donohue 
right now you have to carry your marriage certificate in your 
pocket in denver donohue said before the vote 
there are some people who go around and deliberately turn 
other people in she said there is even one real estate agent 
who sells houses based on the current law telling buyers that no 
one can move in next to them that isnt married this appeals 
particularly to families 
the penalty for violating the citys ordinance is 999 a day in 
many cases if a person is turned in to authorities and owns the 
house they have to sell the house often at a losss donohue said 
donohue said families and one real estate agent are the main 
opponents of change 
among those affected by the ordinance are three nuns who are 
being forced to move out of a fourbedroom home 
they wanted all but one of us to move out said one of the 
nuns who asked that her name not be used to me its wasteful 
to have just one person living in a dwelling with four bedrooms 
its very sinful 
the ban dates back to the 1960s when home owners in some of 
denvers most exclusive neighborhoods feared invasion by hippie 
communes 
so far hundreds of people have violated the ordinance 
including the mexican consul students sharing expenses and 
unmarried couples 
the law is being challenged in court 
