<TEXT>
the supreme court today made it easier for 
those who win partial victories in civil rights lawsuits to recover 
their attorneys fees 
the court in a case involving texas school teachers ruled 
unanimously that those who prevail on a significant issue in 
such suits are entitled to reimbursement for legal fees even if 
they lose the central issue 
the court ruled in favor of teachers in the garland independent 
school district who challenged antiunion regulations imposed by 
school officials 
the regulations barred teacher union representatives from 
visiting schools during regular school hours or using school public 
address systems or other communications facilities 
the rules also prohibited private conversations among teachers 
regarding the employee organizations and also barred any teacher 
from using a schools internal mail system or bulletin board 
facilities 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals upheld the regulations 
affecting union representatives but the appeals court said it 
violates freespeech and freeassociation rights of teachers to ban 
private conversations or prevent them from using the mail or 
bulletin board facilities 
the appeals court also ruled that the texas state teachers 
association and the garland education association which filed the 
suit are not entitled to be reimbursed for attorneys fees 
federal civil rights law provides that the prevailing party 
in such cases is entitled to reimbursement from the losing side 
the idea is to give an incentive to lawyers to represent civil 
rights plaintiffs who may lack the financial resources to hire 
lawyers 
justice sandra day oconnor in her opinion for the high court 
today said the teachers are entitled to reimbursement even though 
they lost the central issue of the case 
she said under federal law a prevailing party must be one who 
has succeeded on any significant claim affording it some of the 
relief sought 
otherwise oconnor said there would have to be 
excruciating inquiries by federal judges to determine the 
intent of lawsuits 
the search for the central and tangential issues in the 
lawsuit or for the primary as opposed to the secondary relief 
sought much like the search for the golden fleece distracts 
judges from the primary purposes of the civil rights law she 
said 
the case is texas state teachers association vs garland 
independent school district 871759 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

