the rugged wilderness that makes prince 
william sound a rich marine habitat stands as a barrier to efforts 
to rescue the thousands of animals expected to be fouled by 
americas biggest oil spill officials say 
theres just a lot of problems out there said pam bergman 
head of the regional response team for the us department of the 
interior 
problems cited by bergman and others include 
a coastline so remote that rescuers are afraid to send out 
volunteers for fear they might not be prepared for wilderness 
survival 
beaches so rugged that in many places it is impossible to land 
a boat let alone chase down and capture oilcoated birds or 
wildlife 
distances to aid facilities so great that animals captured on 
the beach would probably die in captivity waiting to be taken to a 
hospital 
wild animals so large and powerful that rescuers could be 
seriously injured 
