<DOCNO> AP890328-0103 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
chinese will be allowed to sue their government 
under a new law submitted tuesday but a noted legal scholar said 
the legislation comes down heavily on the side of protecting the 
state 
another law also submitted tuesday delineates the powers of 
the national peoples congress chinas legislature it too 
favors a centralization of power 
both laws are expected to pass as submitted during the current 
session of the legislature 
the legislation allowing the lawsuits officially known as the 
administrative procedure law completes a series of legislation 
promulgated since 1979 which aim at instituting a rule of law in 
china 
in 1979 china passed its criminal code law allowing the state 
to take the people to court in 1985 it passed a law on civil 
suits allowing people to sue each other 
under a draft of the new law chinese may sue their government 
and its agencies if their lawful rights and interests have been 
infringed upon by a specific administrative act of an 
administrative organ or its personnel 
infringement can include fines the restriction of freedom 
refusal by an administrative bureau to carry out a task and the 
compulsory seizure of property 
the main problem is that the law allows chinese people to 
challenge the legality of an act but not the law itself thus if 
the government can prove its action was based on a law no suit can 
be brought according to the draft 
zhang shuyi a researcher at the political science and law 
college of china said this problem shows the law doesnt 
adequately protect the interests of the people 
writing in the world economic herald zhang said the law ends 
up protecting the government more than anything else 
the strange thing is that for the longest time weve turned a 
blind eye to the violation of the peoples rights he said but 
at soon as someone says the people should be allowed to sue 
somebody says we have to protect the interests of the government 
since when do we have to protect the power of the 
government he said the goverment by its nature is power 
the key to understanding this problem is that lawmakers and 
executors in china want to ensure the courts dont become too 
powerful he said 
this is not like the united states where they have a 
separation of powers and the various departments battle on an equal 
footing he said the goal is to keep the courts weak 
since the communist revolution in 1949 law was regarded as 
bourgeois and a tool of capitalist society 
but in reality political campaigns and purges since 1957 
culminating in the ultraleftist cultural revolution resulted in a 
massive infringement of basic rights red guards closed the 
schools religion was repressed and people were jailed beaten and 
killed because they were born into a family that once belonged to 
the upper classes 
beginning in 1978 a reform movement to open china to the west 
and introduce elements of a market economy into the staterun 
system pushed change in the legal system 
reformers led by deng xiaoping were concerned they did not 
repeat the abuses of the past they also were sensitive to the 
demands for legal protection for foreign clients who want to do 
business in china 
major problems remain however 
although chinas constitution guarantees freedom of opinion 
thousands of prisoners remain jailed for political beliefs in 
addition the courts remain powerless when compared to the 
communist party and the administrative wing of the government 
an example appeared on the front page of sundays peoples 
daily which reported that three lawyers were arrested and jailed 
for several months because they chose to enter an innocent plea for 
a rape suspect the prosecutors office disagreed with the plea and 
ordered them jailed on charges of protecting a criminal the 
paper said 
their case eventually was taken up by the national peoples 
congress and they were released 
another problem with the legal system concerns the function of 
the congress ostensibly responsible for making laws in china 
under the second piece of legislation submitted tuesday the 
congress can only propose laws after 30 of the approximately 3000 
delegates submit a bill and it passes the inspection of the 
congress presidium 
since the presidium is nominated by the state council chinas 
cabinet the effect of the law is to further centralize government 
power in the councils hands the law known as the rules of 
procedure for the national peoples congress gives the state 
council power to submit legislation directly the communist party 
controls the state council 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

