inmates infected with the aids virus 
will be able to use pseudonyms and wear disguises when they appear 
as witnesses in a trial of their lawsuit against the state a 
federal magistrate has ruled 
but they will have to give their testimony in an open courtroom 
us magistrate joan glazer margolis said monday 
attorneys for the inmates who are suing the state department of 
correction to improve medical care had asked that all proceedings 
be held in a judges chambers and that only edited versions of the 
trial transcripts be made public 
the attorneys from the connecticut civil liberties union and 
yale legal services had argued that strict secrecy was needed to 
protect the prisoners from harassment by other inmates and 
retaliation by the state 
the classaction lawsuit brought by the inmates seeks to force 
the correction department to improve medical care for inmates 
carrying the aids virus and increase aids education and counseling 
for all prisoners 
attorneys for the state had agreed to the use of pseudonyms but 
opposed efforts to close the trial and seal portions of the 
transcripts 
in her ruling margolis noted the importance of protecting the 
privacy of the inmates but said she reluctantly concluded there is 
a less restrictive alternative 
margolis authorized the use of fictitious names by those 
bringing suit and ordered there shall be no testimony of a 
sufficiently detailed nature to compromise their identities 
inmates may also testify in a disguised manner so that he or 
she will not be recognized by facial or other characteristics 
the decision said 
the magistrate held out the possibility she would be willing to 
modify her ruling on a casebycase basis in instances where the 
guidelines are insufficient to protect an identity 
