<TEXT>
a medical equipment manufacturer agreed in a plea 
bargain tuesday to pay 764000 in penalties for selling thousands 
of defective pacemakers and batteries prone to corrosion 
cordis corp pleaded guilty to 12 felony counts and 13 
misdemeanors in the criminal case 
the company agreed last week to pay 5 million to settle a 
civilfraud claim filed by the government four company executives 
still face a criminal trial in september on related charges 
the miamibased company which sold its pacemaker division two 
years ago was accused of distributing 2200 faulty pacemakers and 
6000 batteries subject to corrosion between december 1983 and 
october 1985 
the us food and drug administration charged the pacemakers 
implanted under the skin to regulate the heartbeat could stop 
without warning but no medical emergencies have been linked to the 
devices 
the justice department and cordis had been negotiating a plea 
since last year but us district judge stanley marcus rejected 
one version last october saying the punishment was insufficient 
the company had offered to plead guilty to 24 counts and pay 
264000 in fines and costs 
the agreement accepted by marcus on tuesday added a felony 
charge carrying a 500000 penalty for intent to defraud the fda by 
failing to relay adverse field reports as required 
formal sentencing in the criminal case against the company has 
been set for april 25 marcus is not bound by the restrictions of 
the plea agreement 
the company agreed last week to pay 5 million to settle the 
civil claim by the veterans administration which purchased an 
undisclosed number of the pacemakers and to cover reimbursement 
for devices purchased through medicare and medicaid programs 
cordis spokesman chick mcdowell said there havent been any 
lawsuits filed by people who bought the pacemakers or had them 
implanted by the va 
the justice department said the civil settlement was believed to 
be one of the largest medicare recoveries ever 
cordis general counsel daniel g hall who entered the guilty 
plea on the companys behalf said the company has paid 1 million 
already and the remaining penalty plus interest will be paid within 
three years 
cordis which sold its pacemaker business to the australian 
medical device manufacturer telectronics now concentrates on 
making catheters for diagnosing and treating heart problems and 
gauges for monitoring pressure on the brain 
the company reported net losses of 561 million in 1987 but 
underwent a major restructuring after selling the pacemaker 
operation net earnings for 1988 totaled 24 million on sales of 
132 million 
