<TEXT>
a man who claims he lost his job as a dallas 
high school football coach because he is white should collect 
damages from the school district his attorney told the supreme 
court on tuesday 
but the dallas independent school districts attorney countered 
in oral arguments that norman jett former south oak cliff high 
school coach and athletic director has no right to seek damages 
from a government entity 
jett who said he is now in the building and construction 
business has settled with the principal who transferred him to 
another school frederick todd who is black for 75000 
a federal jury had awarded jett 850000 in damages but he said 
it was reduced to more than 600000 with 10 percent interest for 
five years by a federal trial judge 
jett had coached the south oak cliff football team since 1962 
in the spring of 1983 he was transferred to another high school 
jett had been named head coach and athletic director at south 
oak cliff in 1970 the year the racial composition at the school 
changed from chiefly white to chiefly black todd became the 
schools principal in 1975 
jett claims the school superintendent had the final say on his 
transfer and thus the school district should be held liable for 
damages for violating his civil rights because he says he was a 
victim of racial discrimination 
his attorney frank m gilstrap of arlington texas said that 
even though the school district has an antidiscrimination policy 
it can still be held liable for actions of an employee who violates 
that policy 
school district attorney leonard j schwartz of dallas said a 
persons civil rights are not violated when people cannot seek 
damages from a municipality or school district because they can 
still collect from the individual responsible 
the supreme court is studying a 5th us circuit court of 
appeals ruling that ordered a new trial for jetts lawsuit 
his suit alleged that school officials violated his dueprocess 
freespeech and equalprotection rights 
a jury found that the city school district should be held 
legally liable for what it found to be violations of jetts rights 
but the appeals court ruled that the jury did not make sufficient 
findings to support municipal liability the appeals court 
ordered a new trial for that reason 
the cases are jett vs dallas independent school district 
872084 and dallas independent school district vs jett 88214 
