dore said in a letter to us trade representative carla hills 
but we believe the record of japanese restrictions with respect 
to wood products may be among the most onerous in the pacific rim 
wyden asked hills to investigate allegations from the national 
forest products association that the japanese use duties licensing 
constraints exclusive distribution arrangements and building code 
restrictions to block imports of us wood products into their 
markets 
under federal law wyden said once the investigation is 
complete hills would recommend specific remedies to the 
president 
wyden told hills that recent amendments to the 1974 trade act 
would then require the president to take agressive action against 
these foreign trade barriers up to and including countermeasurers 
affecting japanese imports to the united states if a satisfactory 
resolution cannot be negotiated 
japan recently refused to reopen socalled sectorspecific 
talks on forestry products talks wyden said offered what 
appeared to be the surest and swiftest solution to these trade 
problems 
the national forest productions association said that japanese 
barriers affect such us products as softwood and hardwood logs 
and lumber plywood veneer millwork laminated wood products 
waferboard and particleboard 
the association said that while 22 billion worth of us wood 
products were sold in japan last year over 70 percent involved raw 
materials 
