<TEXT>
afghanistan is preparing for an uncertain spring 
in the aftermath of the soviet troop withdrawal the new delhi 
bureau chief of the associated press who has made periodic 
reporting trips to kabul filed the following report 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the people of this capital dig in the 
earth as it thaws after a fierce winter making defenses for war 
with guerrillas and planting crops to sustain life 
green sprouts are appearing in dun fields within and just 
outside the city more plots are being prepared for planting wheat 
and vegetables 
machines carve trenches inside the airport and along a barren 
ridge that overlooks the runway and is overlooked in turn by 
mountains where the moslem fighters wait and occasionally fire 
rockets at the airport or city 
if you lose the airport youve lost kabul a un official 
said asking that his name not be used theyre building new 
defenses there and strengthening old ones 
the soviet union continues to supply weapons and ammunition but 
for the first spring since 1979 the kremlins client government is 
bereft of direct red army support against the ussupported 
insurgents 
some soviet advisers remain under a friendship treaty predating 
the civil war which began after a communist coup in april 1978 
a soviet colonel who was at the airport in february during the 
final days of the red army withdrawal was seen there about a week 
ago this time in civilian clothes a wellplaced source said 
privately he added that the colonel smiled and said he had retired 
from the armed forces 
most soviets attached to kabul university and government 
ministries left in the past year as the military withdrawal 
progressed afghan and foreign observers say however that air 
traffic controllers and hundreds of other technical workers remain 
un staff members counted 123 soviet transport planes landing 
at the airport during a week in midmarch scudb missiles and 
ammunition crates have been seen being unloaded or taken from the 
airport 
although the afghan government describes it as a food airlift 
the soviets themselves have said they would continue military 
resupply operations 
even if all available land in and immediately around the city is 
planted the crops can feed only about oneeighth of the 22 
million people crowded into the city according to un estimates 
the rest must come by air or on roads subject to guerrilla attack 
harassment and sabotage 
only four major highways connect kabul with the rest of the 
country two lead south and west into guerrilla areas some of 
which are only 15 miles from the city 
the eastern route passes through jalalabad 75 miles away where 
the guerrillas have besieged government forces for three weeks 
that leaves the salang highway which runs through the hindu 
kush mountain range and the northern wheat plain to the soviet 
border 260 miles away 
it passes through territory controlled by ahmed shah masood one 
of the ablest guerrilla commanders buses and some trucks have 
reached kabul on the salang in recent days but masoods men have 
been able to cut the highway in the past 
government and foreign aid workers agree there is no starvation 
in kabul but both say the plight of the poorest residents grows 
worse because supplies are scarce and they cannot meet the rising 
prices 
nan the staple flat bread goes for the frozen price of 6 
afghanis about 10 cents at the official rate of exchange but 
mutton the favorite meat has risen about 40 percent in three 
months while wages remain unchanged 
a kilogram of mutton 22 pounds costs 1000 afghanis 18 at 
the official exchange rate and 450 at the black market rate that 
is onefifth the average monthly pay of a government office worker 
and about half that of an unskilled laborer 
few afghans have access to the black market because they do not 
have the hard foreign currency on which it is based 
tur pekii a 35yearold woman with nine children was among 
1000 people who received free flour and sugar this week from the 
united nations 
she said her husband earned 3000 afghanis a month as a teacher 
54 at the official rate 
we cant find sugar she said through the mesh facepanel of 
a brown chadri veil that enveloped her from head to toe we dont 
want it anyway its too expensive 
sugar has gone since january from 180 afghanis a kilo to 400 
325 to 725 at the official rate 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

