<TEXT>
treasury secretary nicholas f brady assured texas 
business leaders tuesday that federal regulators would not disrupt 
the states fragile economic recovery by flooding the real estate 
market with property obtained from insolvent savings and loan 
institutions 
brady also warned that delaying the bush administrations plan 
for rescuing the nations hundreds of insolvent thrifts was costing 
taxpayers 20 million per day and continued debate over alternative 
proposals would add millions more to the costs 
key elements of the plan call for the government to close some 
350 insolvent but still open thrifts and meet commitments for 205 
institutions rescued last year 
local business leaders frequently have expressed fears that the 
federal government would unload real estate acquired with the 
failed thrifts at belowmarket prices to help clear their books 
such transactions would be carried out by the federal asset 
disposition association which is charged with selling assets from 
failed thrifts or a proposed alternative vehicle 
fada currently manages about assets valued at about 38 billion 
in 33 states of those assets an estimated 259 billion worth are 
in texas 
we understand the potential destructive effects on the local 
economies of wholesale dumping brady said in a speech to the 
greater dallas chamber of commerce let me assure you that we 
intend to proceed very carefully with real estate sales 
decisions will be evaluated and made with the best interest of 
everyone involved particularly local communities taken into 
consideration he said 
brady said the government would be robbing itself by cutrate 
sales which would reduce the money that the sales could generate 
to help finance the rescue plan 
the administration is resisting efforts by sen timothy wirth 
dcolo and other legislators to write dumping obstacles into the 
sampl rescue bill being considered by congress 
bradys first trip this year to texas the state hardest hit by 
the thrift crisis is sandwiched between the end of congressional 
hearings on bushs plan and the expected start of committee work on 
the legislation when lawmakers return next week from their spring 
recess 
the treasury department is working on an alternative operating 
plan for the socalled resolution trust corp the government 
entity in the bush proposal that would liquidate failed sampls 
according to an administration official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
the rtc will be free to consider a number of innovative 
proposals for preventing dumping including the creation of 
regional trusts to buy and manage problem properties or the 
securitization of pools of real estate for sale to public 
investors the official said 
obviously theres some real estate thats junkthat has no 
value now that never did have never will have you might as well 
get that behind you brady said tuesday theres other real 
estate thats wellconceived which has tenants in buildings and 
people living in condosand those kinds of properties shouldnt 
be thrown on the market willynilly and wont be 
the bush plan which would bring thrift regulation under the 
treasury department would spend 40 billion to finance the 
insolvent institutions that already have been taken care of and 
would borrow another 50 billion to be spent during the next three 
years brady said 
the treasury secretary disagreed with past suggestions for a 
onetime lump sum appropriation of taxpayers money to pay for the 
massive thrift rescues he said such an expense would make it 
impossible to meet budget deficit reduction targets which in turn 
would boost government borrowing costs 
we cannot afford delay if the debate over alternate financial 
plans takes even three weeks the cost to the taxpayer goes up by 
500 million brady said said 
