mayor marion barry jr was fined 500 tuesday 
by the district of columbias office of campaign finance for not 
disclosing his partnership with a prominent local developer in a 
nantucket mass real estate deal 
marianne coleman niles who heads the campaign finance office 
determined that a promissory note the mayor signed in 1985 when he 
bought an interest in a nantucket building constituted an 
interestfree loan and should have been listed on barrys financial 
disclosure forms 
however niles concluded that barry did not violate the citys 
conflict of interest statute by entering into the partnership with 
developer jeffrey cohen despite barrys personal approval of some 
of cohens business dealings with the city 
top city officials are required by law to annually disclose any 
liability of more than 1000 that is owed to anyone except family 
members banks or other credit institutions the note obligates 
the mayor to pay 49000 over 10 years for a 10 percent interest in 
the building 
barry failed to list the partnership on his 1986 1987 or 1988 
disclosure forms 
this disclosure policy applies with full force to the mayor 
and every other district of columbia government official niles 
said in a release 
however niles concluded that barry may not have known that he 
was required to disclose the complicated loan deal and concluded 
the mayor did not willfully omit it 
herbert o reid barrys legal counsel wrote niles that barry 
will pay the 500 fine and amend his disclosure forms to include 
the loan but added that barry is operating with the clear 
understanding that he has not engaged in any wrongdoing 
john c white barrys spokesman said the mayor would not 
comment on the matter 
barry could have been fined up to 1500 500 for each failure 
to disclose and niles could have recommended that the us 
attorneys office investigate the matter 
the washington post reported in tuesdays editions that reid 
told niles that barry did not view the arrangement as a loan but 
simply an agreement to pay his 49000 share in installments 
barrys interest in the building was held in the name of another 
investor israel kogan a local obstetrician who served as the 
legal nominee kogan and barry formed an unregistered 
partnership named kb associates 
the building now valued at more than 1 million is owned by 
nine people including barry and cohen situated in the islands 
historic district it houses two antique shops and three apartments 
