<TEXT>
the city attorney filed suit tuesday against 
more than 100 alleged slumlords who trade buildings like cards at 
a card game in order to stay a step ahead of the law 
the lawsuit filed in superior court by city attorney james 
hahn charges lenders and landlords with conspiring to make a 
fortune off poor tenants while sidestepping city building code 
regulations 
the civil case was filed under the federal racketeer influenced 
and corrupt organizations act or rico 
several tenants peered out of windows at a fourstory apartment 
building where hahn held a news conference to announce a crackdown 
on 137 lenders companies and individuals allegedly involved in the 
scheme 
the lawsuit alleges that for years the defendants have engaged 
in a common enterprise and plan directed toward maintaining slum 
buildings without the repairs to make them habitable while 
extracting from them the maximum amount of rent earnings and 
profit 
the landlords allegedly avoided prosecution for building code 
violations by selling the properties after the city filed suit to 
bring them up to code when ownership changes buildings must be 
reinspected before city officials can resume the enforcement 
process 
hahn said the 42unit apartment building where the news 
conference was held had changed hands eight times since 1984 
these guys trade buildings like cards at a card game hahn 
said clearly what they are doing is not normal business 
practice 
the lawsuit seeks unspecified punitive damages for the tenants 
at least 1 million in civil penalties and court orders to repair 
buildings and to prohibit the lenders from continuing alleged 
unfair banking practices 
it involves the ownership of 11 apartment buildings and 
residential hotels that house an estimated 1450 people 
the suit alleges that highland federal savings amp loan 
association and aampb loan co arranged exorbitant loans for decrepit 
buildings and extended credit to property owners with insufficient 
financial resources 
they lend to people who could never buy a house said 
barrett litt a public interest attorney who joined hahn and the 
legal aid foundation in filing the suit 
loans often were so huge that the revenues generated by tenants 
monthly rent went entirely for interest payments and the mortgage 
paid nothing toward the principal hahn said 
however hahn did not paint the landlords as victims of the 
lenders but as their coconspirators 
our evidence will show many instances of fraud and insider 
dealing in transfers that were designed to falsely inflate the 
value of property and subvert criminal prosecutions hahn said 
officials for the two loan companies did not immediately return 
telephone calls seeking comment 
the lawsuit names 135 companies and individuals who allegedly 
worked with the lenders by taking advantage of shell corporations 
or shelters to borrow large amounts of money against the slum 
buildings 
the suit charges the defendants with unfair business practices 
and alleges a number of violations committed against tenants 
including fraud conspiracy breaches of warranty and habitability 
and failure to abate a nuisance 
deborah dentler a legal aid attorney said tenants in most of 
the targeted buildings pay 350 to 550 a month for oneroom 
vermininfested apartments 
in one building she said toilets and showers were perpetually 
clogged and there were no light bulbs in hallways tenants must 
confront drug addicts cockroaches crawling over their children 
mice and deteriorating plumbing fixtures she said 
</TEXT>
