<TEXT>
at least 15 people were killed as 
filipinos chose village leaders tuesday the government hailed the 
voting as the final step in restoring democracy three years after 
the marcos era ended 
the military claimed communist rebels would use the elections to 
expand their control in rural areas by pressuring voters into 
endorsing proguerrilla candidates 
election officials said it would take days or weeks to assess 
the extent of rebel influence on the balloting 
voters in more than 41000 villages and urban wards chose about 
287567 council members from more than 860000 candidates it 
marked the fourth nationwide balloting since president corazon 
aquino took power three years ago and ferdinand marcos the 
president for 20 years fled into hawaiian exile 
scattered violence but no major incidents were reported 
the military said gunmen killed one person and wounded three as 
they went to a polling station in tupi in south cotabato province 
on mindanao island 
also in mindanao two gunmen killed a candidate sunday in tubura 
in bukidnon province and then were themselves killed by lawmen 
reports said 
other killings occurred in luzon island samar island and aklan 
province 
a candidate died monday when a truck ran over him while he was 
supervising a road repair project in marbel in northern cotabato a 
military report said 
the elections were nonpartisan but political analysts said the 
outcome will influence national politics by enabling political 
factions to establish grassroots organizations prior to the 1992 
presidential election 
col gerardo flores intelligence chief of the philippine 
constabulary said communist rebels were backing candidates in 
hopes of capturing 60 percent of the council seats in areas under 
their control 
the rebels claim to control about 8500 villages nationwide and 
to operate in 3500 more the commission on election estimates the 
rebels control about 2800 villages and urban wards the difference 
is believed to lie in defining control 
tuesdays elections are the last scheduled before the 1992 
presidential vote 
voters ratified a new constitution in february 1987 selected 
members of a twochamber congress the following may and chose 
provincial officials mayors and city council members in january 
1988 
